    <para id="para-00001">We’ve already seen several reactions of alcohols—their conversion into alkyl halides and tosylates in <link document="m00117"/> and their dehydration to give alkenes in <link document="m00089"/>—albeit without mechanistic details. Let’s now look at those details.</para>
    <section id="sect-00001">
    <title>Conversion of Alcohols into Alkyl Halides</title>
    <para id="para-00002">Tertiary alcohols react with either HCl or HBr at 0 °C by an S<sub>N</sub>1 mechanism through a carbocation intermediate. Primary and secondary alcohols are much more resistant to acid, however, and are best converted into halides by treatment with either SOCl<sub>2</sub> or PBr<sub>3</sub> through an S<sub>N</sub>2 mechanism.</para>
    <para id="para-00003">The reaction of a tertiary alcohol with HX takes place by an S<sub>N</sub>1 mechanism when acid protonates the hydroxyl oxygen atom. Water is expelled to generate a carbocation, and the cation reacts with nucleophilic halide ion to give the alkyl halide product.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00001">
    <media alt="An illustration shows “a tertiary alcohol” reacting with HCl having pink hydrogen and blue chlorine or HBr having pink hydrogen and blue bromine to form an intermediate compound shown in parentheses involving SN1 mechanism to yield a carbocation which further reacts with blue chlorine anion or blue bromine anion to form “an alkyl chloride or bromide.” The structure of a tertiary alcohol shows a carbon wedge bonded to an R dash bonded to an R and single bonded to an R on the left and to pink hydroxyl group on the right. The reactant of the intermediate reaction shows a carbon wedge bonded to an R dash bonded to an R and single bonded to “R” on the left and to a pink oxygen cation on the right that is bonded to two pink hydrogens; a pink arrow points from carbon and hydroxyl bond to the oxygen cation. The product of the intermediate reaction is a carbocation having a carbon cation dash bonded to an R and wedge bonded to an R at the top and single bonded to “R” at the bottom; a pink water molecule is shown above the carbocation. The alkyl chloride or bromide shows a carbon wedge bonded to an R dash bonded to an R and single bonded to an R on the left and to a blue chlorine or bromine on the right.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_17_06_001.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00004">The reactions of primary and secondary alcohols with SOCl<sub>2</sub> and PBr<sub>3</sub> take place by S<sub>N</sub>2 mechanisms. Hydroxide ion itself is too poor a leaving group to be displaced by nucleophiles in S<sub>N</sub>2 reactions, but reaction of an alcohol with SOCl<sub>2</sub> or PBr<sub>3</sub> converts the –OH into a much better leaving group, either a chlorosulfite (–OSOCl) or a dibromophosphite (–OPBr<sub>2</sub>), which is readily expelled by backside nucleophilic substitution.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00002">
    <media alt="A two-part illustration shows reactions for a single reactant. In the first reaction “A primary or secondary alcohol” with pink hydroxyl group reacts with blue SOCl2 and ether to form “a chlorosulfite” in parentheses which undergoes SN2 mechanism to form “an alkyl chloride” SO2 having pink oxygen and blue “S” and “2” and HCl having pink H and blue Cl. In the second reaction the primary or secondary alcohol reacts with blue PBr3 and ether to form “a dibromophosphite” in parentheses which undergoes SN2 mechanism to form “an alkyl bromide” and Br2POH having blue Br2P and pink OH. The structure of primary or secondary alcohol shows a carbon having open dash and wedge bonds and a hydrogen bonded to the lower left position a pink hydroxyl group is bonded on the right. The chlorosulfite shows a carbon having open dash and wedge bonds and a hydrogen bonded to the lower left position on the right the carbon is bonded to a pink oxygen is bonded to a blue sulfur double bonded to an oxygen on top and the sulfur bonds to a blue chlorine on the right; a blue chlorine anion is placed on the left above the structure; a pink arrow points from the chlorine anion to the carbon another pink arrow points from C - pink O bond to the pink O - blue S bond; the third arrow points from S-Cl bond to Cl. An alkyl chloride shows a blue chlorine bonded to a carbon having an open dash and wedge bonds and a single bond with hydrogen. The dibromophosphite shows a carbon having open dash and wedge bonds and a hydrogen bonded to the lower left position on the right the carbon is bonded to a pink oxygen bonded to a blue PBr2 on the right; a blue bromine anion is placed on the left above the structure; a pink arrow points from the bromine anion to the carbon another pink arrow points from C - pink O bond to the pink O. An alkyl bromide shows a blue bromine bonded to carbon having an open wedge and dash bonds and to a hydrogen.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_17_06_002.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    </section>
    <section id="sect-00002">
    <title>Conversion of Alcohols into Tosylates</title>
    <para id="para-00005">Alcohols react with <emphasis effect="italics">p</emphasis>-toluenesulfonyl chloride (tosyl chloride, <emphasis effect="italics">p</emphasis>-TosCl) in pyridine solution to yield alkyl tosylates, ROTos (<link document="m00122"/>). Only the O–H bond of the alcohol is broken in this reaction; the C–O bond remains intact, so no change of configuration occurs if the oxygen is attached to a chirality center. The resultant alkyl tosylates behave much like alkyl halides, undergoing both S<sub>N</sub>1 and S<sub>N</sub>2 substitution reactions.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00003">
    <media alt="An illustration shows “an alcohol” reacting with “p-Toluenesulfonyl chloride” in the presence of pyridine to form “a tosylate (ROTos) and “pyridine. pink HCl.” The structural formula of alcohol shows pink R bonded to pink oxygen bonded to pink hydrogen. The structure of p-Toluenesulfonyl chloride shows a benzene bonded to sulfur having two double bonds with oxygens and a single bond with pink chlorine the lower right position on the ring is bonded to a methyl group. The structure of a tosylate shows a benzene bonded to sulfur having two double bonds with oxygens and a single bond with pink oxygen bonded to pink R; the lower right position on the ring is bonded to a methyl group.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_17_06_003.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00006">One of the most important reasons for using tosylates in S<sub>N</sub>2 reactions is stereochemical. The S<sub>N</sub>2 reaction of an alcohol with an alkyl halide proceeds with two inversions of configuration—one to make the halide from the alcohol and one to substitute the halide—and yields a product with the same stereochemistry as the starting alcohol. The S<sub>N</sub>2 reaction of an alcohol with a tosylate, however, proceeds with only one inversion and yields a product of opposite stereochemistry to the starting alcohol. <link target-id="fig-00004"/> shows a series of reactions on the <emphasis effect="italics">R</emphasis> enantiomer of 2-octanol that illustrates these stereochemical relationships.</para>
    <figure id="fig-00004">
    <media alt="A two-part illustration shows two reactions of (R)-2-Octanol. In the first reaction “(R)-2-Octanol” reacts with green PBr3 and ether to form “(S)-2-Bromooctane” which undergoes SN2 mechanism in the presence of blue sodium ethoxide salt to form “Ethyl (R)-1-methylheptyl ether. In the second reaction “(R)-2-Octanol” reacts with green p-TosCl and pyridine to form “(R)-1-Methylheptyl tosylate” which undergoes SN2 mechanism in the presence of blue sodium ethoxide salt to form “Ethyl (S)-1-methylheptyl ether.” The structural formula of (R)-2-Octanol shows a methyl group bonded to five methylene groups bonded to a carbon dash bonded to a pink hydroxyl group at the top and wedge bonded to a hydrogen at the top; the carbon is bonded to a methyl group at the bottom. The structural formula of (S)-2-Bromooctane shows a methyl group bonded to five methylene groups bonded to a carbon dash bonded to pink hydroxyl group and wedge bonded to a green bromine at the top; the carbon is bonded to a methyl group at the bottom. Ethyl (R)-1-methylheptyl ether shows a methyl group bonded to five methylene groups bonded to a carbon dash bonded to blue ethoxide group and wedge bonded to a hydrogen at the top; the carbon is bonded to a methyl group at the bottom. The structural formula of (R)-1-Methylheptyl tosylate shows a methyl group bonded to five methylene groups bonded to a carbon dash bonded to pink oxygen attached to green Tos and wedge bonded to a hydrogen at the top; the carbon is bonded to a methyl group at the bottom. The structural formula of Ethyl (S)-1-methylheptyl ether shows a methyl group bonded to five methylene groups bonded to a carbon dash bonded to a hydrogen and wedge bonded to a blue ethoxide group at the top; the carbon is bonded to a methyl group at the bottom.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_17_06_004.jpg"/>
    </media>
    <caption><emphasis effect="bold">Stereochemical consequences of S<sub>N</sub>2 reactions on derivatives of (<emphasis effect="italics">R</emphasis>)-2-octanol</emphasis>. Substitution through the halide gives a product with the same stereochemistry as the starting alcohol; substitution through the tosylate gives a product with opposite stereochemistry to the starting alcohol.</caption>
    </figure>
    </section>
