    <section id="sect-00004">
    <title>Dehydration of Alcohols to Yield Alkenes</title>
    <para id="para-00008">A third important reaction of alcohols, both in the laboratory and in biological pathways, is their dehydration to give alkenes. Because of the usefulness of the reaction, a number of methods have been devised for carrying out dehydrations. One method that works particularly well for tertiary alcohols is the acid-catalyzed reaction discussed in <link document="m00089"/>. For example, treatment of 1-methylcyclohexanol with warm, aqueous sulfuric acid in a solvent such as tetrahydrofuran results in loss of water and formation of 1-methylcyclohexene.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down-30" id="fig-00005">
    <media alt="An illustration shows “1-methylcyclohexanol” reacting with hydronium ion THF at 50 degree C to form “1-methylcyclohexene (91%).” The structure of 1-methylcyclohexanol shows a cyclohexane bonded to a methyl group and a pink hydroxyl group at the tip of ring; the structure of 1-methylcyclohexene shows a cyclohexene bonded to a methyl group.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_17_06_006.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00009">Acid-catalyzed dehydrations usually follow Zaitsev’s rule (<link document="m00128"/>) and yield the more stable alkene as the major product. Thus, 2-methyl-2-butanol gives primarily 2-methyl-2-butene (trisubstituted double bond) rather than 2-methyl-1-butene (disubstituted double bond).</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00006">
    <media alt="An illustration shows a reaction wherein “2-Methyl-2-butanol” reacts with hydronium ion THF at 25 degree C to form “2-Methyl-2-butene (trisubstituted)” a “pink major product” and “2-Methyl-1-butene (disubstituted)” a “minor product.” The structure of 2-Methyl-2-butanol shows a methyl group bonded to a carbon bonded to a methyl group at the top and to a pink hydroxyl group at the bottom; the carbon is further bonded to an ethyl group on the right. 2-Methyl-2-butene shows a carbon bonded to two methyl groups on the left and double bonded to a methine group attached to a methyl group on the right. 2-Methyl-1-butene shows a carbon double bonded to two methyl groups on the left and an ethyl group on the right.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_17_06_007.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00010">This reaction is an E1 process (<link document="m00131"/>) and occurs by the three-step mechanism shown in <link target-id="fig-00007"/> on the next page. Protonation of the alcohol oxygen is followed by unimolecular loss of water to generate a carbocation intermediate and final loss of a proton from the neighboring carbon atom to complete the process. As with most E1 reactions, tertiary alcohols react fastest because they lead to stabilized, tertiary carbocation intermediates. Secondary alcohols can be made to react, but the conditions are severe (75% H<sub>2</sub>SO<sub>4</sub>, 100 °C) and sensitive molecules don’t survive.</para>
    <figure class="mechanism-figure scaled-down" id="fig-00007">
    <title>MECHANISM</title>
    <media alt="An illustration three steps involved in the acid catalysis dehydration of a tertiary alcohol along with their reversible associated structures. In step 1 the tertiary alcohol reacts with pink hydronium ion to yield protonated alcohol. The tertiary alcohol shows a cyclohexane bonded to a methyl group and a pink oxygen having two pairs of electrons bonded to a pink hydrogen; in hydronium ion a pink hydrogen is bonded to an oxygen cation having a pair of electrons and bonded to two hydrogens. An arrow points from the hydroxyl oxygen bonded to the ring to a hydrogen of hydronium ion; another arrow points from the pink H-O bond to O. Text reads: Two electrons from the oxygen atom bond to H plus yielding a protonated alcohol intermediate. In step 2 the protonated alcohol yields a carbocation. The protonated alcohol shows a cyclohexane bonded to a methyl group and a pink oxygen cation having two pairs of electrons bonded to two pink hydrogens. An arrow from the C1-O bond points to O. Text reads: The carbon-oxygen bond breaks and the two electrons from the bond stay with oxygen leaving a carbocation intermediate. In step 3 the carbocation reacts with pink water where the oxygen shows four electrons and yields an alkene and hydronium ion; the structure of carbocation shows a cyclohexane with C1 a cation bonded to a methyl group. C2 is bonded to a hydrogen and a blue hydrogen. An arrow from the electrons of oxygen points to blue hydrogen. An arrow from the C2-blue hydrogen bond points to C1-C2 bond. Text reads: Two electrons from a neighboring carbon-hydrogen bond form the alkene pi bond and H plus (a proton) is eliminated. The alkene shows a cyclohexene bonded to a methyl group at C1 and to a hydrogen at C2.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_17_06_009.jpg"/>
    </media>
    <caption><emphasis effect="bold">Mechanism for the acid-catalyzed dehydration of a tertiary alcohol to yield an alkene</emphasis>. The process is an E1 reaction and involves a carbocation intermediate.</caption>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00011">To circumvent the need for strong acid and allow the dehydration of secondary alcohols in a gentler way, reagents have been developed that are effective under mild, basic conditions. One such reagent, phosphorus oxychloride (POCl<sub>3</sub>) in the basic amine solvent pyridine, is often able to effect the dehydration of secondary and tertiary alcohols at 0 °C.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down-30" id="fig-00008">
    <media alt="An illustration shows a reaction wherein “1-Methylcyclohexanol” reacts with green POCl3 and pyridine at 0 degree C to form “1-methylcyclohexene (96%).” The structure of 1-Methylcyclohexanol shows a cyclohexane bonded to a methyl group and a pink hydroxyl group at the top right position. The structure of 1-methylcyclohexene shows a cyclohexene bonded to a methyl group and a hydrogen at two adjoining positions of the double bond.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_17_06_008.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00012">Alcohol dehydrations carried out with POCl<sub>3</sub> in pyridine take place by an E2 mechanism, as shown in <link target-id="fig-00009"/>. Because hydroxide ion is a poor leaving group (<link document="m00124"/>), direct E2 elimination of water from an alcohol does not occur. On reaction with POCl<sub>3</sub>, however, the –OH group is converted into a dichlorophosphate (–OPOCl<sub>2</sub>), which is a good leaving group and is readily eliminated. Pyridine is both the reaction solvent and the base that removes a neighboring proton in the E2 elimination step.</para>
    <figure class="mechanism-figure scaled-down" id="fig-00009">
    <title>MECHANISM</title>
    <media alt="An illustration shows two steps involving dehydration of secondary and tertiary alcohols. The first step reads “the alcohol hydroxyl group reacts with POCl3 to form a dichlorophosphate intermediate”; the alcohol group is shown as a cyclohexane bonded to a pink hydroxyl group having an oxygen with two pairs of electrons; green POCl3 is shown as an oxygen double bonded to phosphorous bonded to three chlorine atoms; a pink arrow points from the oxygen of OH group to the phosphorous; another arrow points from the third bond between P and Cl to Cl; the intermediate in parentheses shows a cyclohexane bonded to a blue hydrogen and a pink oxygen attached to green POCl2; a blue benzene ring having nitrogen with a pair of electrons is shown embedded in it; an arrow points from nitrogen to hydrogen; another arrow points from hydrogen cyclohexane bond to the next adjacent position; third arrow points from cyclohexane and pink oxygen bond to oxygen. The second step reads “E2 elimination then occurs by the usual one-step mechanism as the amine base pyridine abstracts a proton from the neighboring carbon at the same time that the dichlorophosphate group is leaving”; the alkene formed shows a cylclohexene.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_17_06_010.jpg"/>
    </media>
    <caption><emphasis effect="bold">Mechanism for the dehydration of secondary and tertiary alcohols by reaction with POCl<sub>3</sub> in pyridine</emphasis>. The reaction is an E2 process.</caption>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00013">As noted in <link document="m00132"/>, biological dehydrations are also common and usually occur by an E1cB mechanism on a substrate in which the –OH group is two carbons away from a carbonyl group. One example occurs in the biosynthesis of the aromatic amino acid tyrosine. A base (<emphasis effect="bold">:</emphasis>B) first abstracts a proton from the carbon adjacent to the carbonyl group, and the anion intermediate then expels the –OH group with simultaneous protonation by an acid (HA) to form water.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered" id="fig-00010">
    <media alt="An illustration shows steps involved in the synthesis of tyrosine. 5-Dehydroquinate forms an anion intermediate shown in parentheses that releases pink water molecule to form 5-dehydroshikimate which further reacts to form tyrosine. 5-dehydroquinate shows a cyclohexanone with C2 bonded to two blue hydrogens C3 dash bonded to a pink hydroxyl group and wedge bonded to a carboxylate ion C5 wedge bonded to a hydroxyl group and dash bonded to a hydrogen and C6 dash bonded to a hydroxyl group and wedge bonded to a hydrogen. A blue “B” with a pair of electrons is shown on the left of structure; a pink arrow points from electrons to a blue H another arrow points from C2-H bond to C2. The anion intermediate is similar to the reactant but C2 shows a negative charge and two electrons. An arrow from C2-C3 bond points to C3-C4 bond. A pink A-H is shown above the structure on the left; a pink arrow points from C3-OH dash bond to H of H-A; the third arrow points from H-A bond to A. 5-Dehydroshikimate shows a cyclohexenone with a double bond at C2 C3 single bonded to a carboxylate ion C5 wedge bonded to a hydroxyl group and dash bonded to a hydrogen and C6 dash bonded to a hydroxyl group and wedge bonded to a hydrogen. Tyrosine shows a benzene bonded to a pink hydroxyl group on the lower left; the upper right is bonded to a 2-carbon chain with C2 of the chain dash bonded to hydrogen and wedge bonded to blue ammonium ion and single bonded to carboxylate ion.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_17_06_011.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    </section>
