    <section id="sect-00006">
    <title>Conversion of Alcohols into Esters</title>
    <para id="para-00015">Alcohols react with carboxylic acids to give esters, a reaction that is common in both the laboratory and living organisms. In the laboratory, the reaction can be carried out in a single step if a strong acid is used as catalyst. More frequently, though, the reactivity of the carboxylic acid is enhanced by first converting it into a carboxylic acid chloride, which then reacts with the alcohol.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered" id="fig-00011">
    <media alt="A two-part illustration shows the cyclic reactions of benzoic acid. The first reaction shows benzoic acid reacting with pink methanol HCl and heat to form methyl benzoate (an ester). Another reaction shows benzoic acid reacting with blue SOCl2 to form benzoyl chloride (a carboxylic acid chloride) which reacts with pink methanol to form methyl benzoate. Benzoic acid shows benzene bonded to a carbonyl group with pink oxygen the carbon of carbonyl group is bonded to a green hydroxyl group Methyl benzoate shows a benzene bonded to a carbonyl group with pink oxygen the carbon of carbonyl group is bonded to a pink methoxide group. Benzoyl chloride shows a benzene bonded to a carbonyl group with pink oxygen the carbon of carbonyl group is bonded to a blue chlorine.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_17_06_013.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00016">In living organisms, a similar process occurs, though a thioester or acyl adenosyl phosphate acts as substrate rather than a carboxylic acid chloride. We’ll look at the mechanisms of these reactions in Chapter 21.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down-30" id="fig-00012">
    <media alt="An illustration shows two reactants forming a common product “an ester” in the presence of a pink ROH. The first reactant is a thioester shown as a central carbonyl group having a pink oxygen; on the left is an open bond intersected by a pink spiral line is shown; on the right green SR is bonded. The second reactant “an acyl adenosyl phosphate” shows a carbonyl group having a pink oxygen; on the left is an open bond intersected by a pink spiral line is shown; on the right a green oxygen bonded to green phosphorous double bonded to a green oxygen and single bonded to an oxygen anion at the top phosphorous is bonded to another oxygen at the bottom which is further bonded to an adenosine. The ester shows a central carbonyl group having a pink oxygen; on the left is an open bond intersected by a pink spiral line is shown; on the right pink OR is bonded.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_17_06_014.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
